redcap:Alerts.email_subject: TIPS to reduce your risk of COVID-19
redcap:Alerts.alert_message:
Hi [p_firstname],

Thanks for registering. Here is some helpful ways you can reduce the spread.

  1. WASH hands often with soap and running water, or alcohol sanitiser.
  2. DRY with paper towel or hand dryer.
  3. TRY not to touch your eyes, nose or mouth.
  4. COVER your nose and mouth with a tissue when you cough or sneeze.
  5. ISOLATE yourself at home if you feel sick.
  6. PHONE your GP first if you need medical attention.
  7. CONTINUE healthy habits: exercise, drink water, get plenty of sleep.

ELECTRONIC NOTIFICATION

Dear Ward Clerk,

A new return traveler has registered their details with the new e-Registration portal.

Could you please:

1. Check to see if they are already registered today.

if they are, please check that the details they have provided match what is already recorded in Epic.

OR

2. If they are not registered today, please create a new attendance today.

redcap:Alerts.email_from_display: Royal Melbourne Hospital Covid Screening Clinic
redcap:Alerts.email_subject: Ten ways to reduce your risk of coronavirus
redcap:Alerts.alert_message:
Hi [p_firstname],

Just thought we would send you a handy email with some tips about staying healthy and avoiding the transfer of coronavirus.

Feel free to stick a poster up a work!

RMH Covid Team.

Ten ways to reduce your risk of coronavirus

  • Washhands often with soap and running water, for at least 20 seconds.Drywith paper towel or hand dryer.
  • Trynot to touch your eyes, nose or mouth.
  • Coveryour nose and mouth with a tissue when you cough or sneeze. If you dont have a tissue cough or sneeze into your upper sleeve or elbow.
  • Isolateyourself at home if you feel sick. If you take medication ensure you have adequate supplies.
  • Phoneyour GP first if you need medical attention. They will tell you what to do.
  • Continuehealthy habits: exercise, drink water, get plenty of sleep, and now is the time to quit smoking. Call the Quitline 137 848.
  • Don'twear a face mask if you are well.
  • Buyan alcohol-based hand sanitiser with over 60 per cent alcohol.
  • Getthe flu shot (available April).
  • Shaking handsis optional!

Dear Sir/Madam,

Regarding: [p_firstname] [p_lastname]

[p_firstname] presented to the Royal Melbourne Hospital COVID-19 screening clinic, and underwent testing for COVID-19 at [timestamp].

In line with current recommendations from the Victorian Department of Health and Human Services, we have discharged [p_firstname] into home isolation, until we get back the results of testing. This process normally takes approximately 24hrs, although currently of state testing services are under significant strain, and results may be delayed.

We appreciate your efforts to support employees during this period.

Yours sincerely,

Dr Mark Putland

Assoc. Prof. Mark Putland

Director, Department of Emergency Medicine

The Royal Melbourne Hospital - City Campus | Emergency Department, Level 1

Grattan Street, Parkville Victoria 3050

T: +61 3 9342 4875|Mark.Putland@mh.org.au

redcap:Alerts.email_subject: Important information for you about home isolation.
redcap:Alerts.alert_message:
Dear [p_firstname],

Now that you have been swabbed, you will need to undertake home isolation until we know the result of your swab. We take home isolation seriously.

Please read the attached document from the Royal Melbourne Hospital which will explain more about this process, and how to follow up your results.

Further information on home isolation can be found here:

https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-isolation-guidance

Yours Sincerely,

The Corona Virus Team @RMH.

Dear Sir/Madam,

Regarding: [p_firstname] [p_lastname]

[p_firstname] presented to the Royal Melbourne Hospital for assessment of their risk of having aquired COVID-19 on the [datestamp].

This letter is to certify that [p_firstname] has been determined to be at low risk of having acquired COVID-19, and does not meet the Department of Health and Human Services requirement for testing.

As such [p_firstname] should continue to engage normally in employment, education and social activities.

Thank you for supporting your employees during this period.

Yours sincerely,

Associate Professor Mark Putland
Director Emergency Medicine
The Royal Melbourne Hospital

You need to get checked out! Dear [p_firstname], it sounds like you have either a) reported symptoms that mean you should be reviewed by our nurse OR b) belong to a group who is identified for additional screeening in the Department of Health's "epidemiological criteria"
